  <text>
    <body>
      <p><persName ref="#ehri_et_schaechter_fischer">Fischer Schaechter</persName>Testimony (doc. 301/201)</p>
      <p>Typescript, 1 page, 210 x 295 mm, Polish language</p>
      <p><persName ref="#ehri_et_schaechter_fischer">Fischer Schaechter</persName>, <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">son</term> of
        <persName ref="#ehri_et_schaechter_eliasz">Eliasz</persName>.</p>
      <p>Born on <date when="1933-05-22">May 22, 1933</date> in <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/712423/berehove.html">Beregsas</placeName> (<placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/719819/hungary.html">Hungary</placeName>). <note type="gloss"
          >Beregszasz, today Berehovo (Ukraine)</note></p>
      <p>In <date when="1942">1942</date>, he was <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject"
          >deported</term> with his <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">family</term>
        to Polish
        <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/690791/ukraine.html">Ukraine</placeName>. He
        survived the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532"
          type="subject">shootings</term> of Jews in <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/709034/halych.html">Halicz</placeName>, a <term
          type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-346">pogrom</term>
        in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/707471/ivano-frankivsk.html"
          >Stanisławów</placeName>. Then, for a year or so, he wandered with his <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">family</term>
        from one place to another, as <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_ukrainians"
          >Ukrainians</term>. In mid-<date when="1943">1943</date> they arrived in <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/688746/vynohradiv.html">Nagymzolos</placeName>. <note
          type="gloss">Nagyszöllos, today Vinohradiv (Ukraine).</note> They lived there as <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373" type="subject">Aryans</term>
        until the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject"
          >ghetto</term> was created one day after the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject"
          >Germans</term> arrived in the town. In <date when="1944-05">May 1944</date> he arrived at
          <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2" type="camp">Oświęcim
          [Auschwitz] (Brzezinka)</placeName>. A tattooed <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">number</term>
        A 5107. Right after he arrived there with his <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject"
        >brother</term>, as twins they were sent aside, to the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491" type="subject">hospital
          (Krankenbau)</term>. Nine times his blood was <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-495" type="subject">drawn</term>,
        his nails were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-495"
          type="subject">measured</term>, all parts of his body were measured under the supervision
        of <foreign xml:lang="de">Obersturmführer – Lagerarzt</foreign>
        <note type="gloss">Oberstürmführer – SS rank equal to Oberleutnant (lieutenant). Lagerarzt
          (German) – camp doctor. Research on twins was made by infamous doctor Josef Mengele,
          having the rank of Hauptstürmführer (captain).</note> Many <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">twins</term>,
        (mostly girls) died after these <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-495" type="subject"
          >experiments</term>. The <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">twin
          brothers</term> did not even receive regular <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-834" type="subject">food
          rations</term> and had to <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term>
        hard [moving] stones.</p>
